---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .check-row {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 44px 1fr;
      gap: 12px;
      padding: 12px 14px;
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
      background: var(--muted);
      margin-bottom: 8px;
    }
    .check-row .check-tag {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 10.5px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.08em;
      padding-top: 2px;
    }
    .check-row .check-body { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .check-row .check-body strong { color: var(--text); }
    .pillar-card {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 20px;
      background: var(--card);
    }
    .pillar-card h3 { font-size: 15px; margin: 0 0 4px; }
    .pillar-sub {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 10.5px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.1em;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="12 · Compliance Stack — Sardis Canvas" currentId="compliance">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 12 · Product</span>
        <h1>Compliance Stack</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          The SDK is the distribution. Compliance is the moat. No fintech partner, no regulated merchant,
          and no enterprise buyer will let an AI agent move real money through them without seeing a
          credible KYC + AML + sanctions + travel-rule + SAR stack behind the API. Sardis ships one.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          Six pillars: <strong>KYC</strong> for humans (Didit), <strong>KYB</strong> for organizations,
          <strong>KYA</strong> for agents, <strong>AML + sanctions</strong> for addresses and counterparties,
          <strong>Travel Rule</strong> for cross-VASP transfers above $3K, and <strong>SAR</strong> for
          regulator-bound suspicious activity reports. All of it runs inside the
          <code>PreExecutionPipeline</code> on the fail-closed side of the gate.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Why -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Why this is the moat</div>
          <h2>Anyone can write a payment SDK. Almost nobody ships compliance.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Every payments-for-agents startup demo looks the same on day one: a wallet, a signed
            transaction, a receipt. The hard part is day 90 — when a regulated merchant wants to onboard,
            the bank wants a BSA report, the auditor asks for retention policy, and the OFAC list just
            got a new entry. These aren't optional; they're the line between a demo and a business.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">What partners ask for</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Stripe Connect onboarding · Circle business account · Bridge originator · Striga banking —
              every one of these started with the same question: <em>"show us your KYC / AML / SAR
              program and your retention policy"</em>. Without those, there is no bank rail, no payout,
              no card issuing. Sardis exists as a platform because the compliance stack exists first.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Why the SDK doesn't replace it</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              SDKs are distribution — they get Sardis into an agent. They don't move money, don't hold
              KYC records, and don't satisfy a regulator. The compliance layer is what makes the SDK's
              output actually spendable. You can't fork your way around FinCEN 5-year retention.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Six pillars -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">The six pillars</div>
          <h2>What actually runs.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Each pillar is a concrete module in <code>packages/sardis-compliance/src/sardis_compliance/</code>
            with its own provider abstraction, its own persistence, and its own tests.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-sub">Pillar 1 · KYC</div>
            <h3>Know Your Customer — for human users.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              Primary provider: <strong>Didit</strong> (YC W26, $0.33/check, 500 free/mo). Document +
              liveness + face match. Persona and Coinbase verifications sit behind the same interface.
              Module: <code>sardis_compliance/kyc.py</code> + provider <code>providers/didit.py</code>.
              Persistence: <code>kyc_verifications</code> (fixed to TEXT agent_id + <code>kyc_status</code>
              on users in migration 090).
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-sub">Pillar 2 · KYB</div>
            <h3>Know Your Business — for organizations.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              Required before an organization can deploy agents that move money above threshold. Module:
              <code>sardis_compliance/kyb.py</code>. Table: <code>kyb_verifications</code> (migration
              010) — inquiry_id, provider, status, verified_at, expires_at, business_name. Triggered at
              organization onboarding, rechecked on anniversary.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-sub">Pillar 3 · KYA</div>
            <h3>Know Your Agent — the Sardis original.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              Human KYC and business KYB don't cover the thing actually signing: the agent. KYA captures
              agent identity (Ed25519/ECDSA-P256 keys), attestation, heartbeat, and state transitions
              (register · check · upgrade · suspend · reactivate · stale sweep). Module:
              <code>sardis_compliance/kya.py</code>. Ties to <code>agit_policy_engine</code> at decision
              time.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-sub">Pillar 4 · AML + Sanctions</div>
            <h3>OFAC, PEP, adverse media, on-chain.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              Providers behind one interface: OFAC, OpenSanctions, Chainalysis, Scorechain, Watchman,
              Elliptic (planned). Screens <em>addresses</em> (on-chain counterparty), <em>entities</em>
              (PEP / sanctions lists), and <em>transactions</em> (combined). Module:
              <code>sanctions.py</code> · <code>pep.py</code> · <code>adverse_media.py</code>. Blocked
              addresses cached with TTL.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-sub">Pillar 5 · Travel Rule</div>
            <h3>FATF R.16 — originator + beneficiary data.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              Migration 012 defines <code>travel_rule_transfers</code>: transfer_id, amount, originator
              and beneficiary JSONB, protocol (e.g., Notabene). Triggered above $3K USD / $1K EUR.
              Module: <code>travel_rule.py</code> + <code>providers/notabene.py</code>. Without this,
              VASP-to-VASP transfers are not legally clean.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="pillar-card">
            <div class="pillar-sub">Pillar 6 · SAR</div>
            <h3>Suspicious Activity Reports — FinCEN 5-year retention.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              <code>suspicious_activity_reports</code> (migration 011) — sar_id, internal_reference,
              activity_type, priority, subject, filing_deadline, report_data. Auto-drafted from anomaly
              scoring; filed by humans. Module: <code>sar.py</code>. Five-year retention is a hard legal
              constraint; the schema is designed for it.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- KYC onboarding flow -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">KYC · Didit flow</div>
          <h2>Signup to <code>sk_live_</code> key in four steps.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Router: <code>packages/server-api/src/sardis_server/routes/compliance/kyc_onboarding.py</code>. Webhook
            delivery is where a dashboard user becomes a fully provisioned Sardis tenant.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="check-row">
            <div class="check-tag">01</div>
            <div class="check-body">
              <strong>Initiate.</strong> <code>POST /v1/onboarding/kyc/initiate</code> creates a Didit
              session (document + liveness). Returns a hosted URL the dashboard redirects to.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="check-row">
            <div class="check-tag">02</div>
            <div class="check-body">
              <strong>User verifies.</strong> On Didit's hosted UI. No PII crosses Sardis at this step.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="check-row">
            <div class="check-tag">03</div>
            <div class="check-body">
              <strong>Webhook.</strong> <code>POST /v1/onboarding/kyc/webhook</code> — Didit posts the
              decision with <code>x-api-key</code> auth. Row inserted into <code>kyc_verifications</code>;
              <code>users.kyc_status</code> flipped to <code>verified</code> / <code>denied</code>.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="check-row">
            <div class="check-tag">04</div>
            <div class="check-body">
              <strong>Live key issued.</strong> On <code>verified</code>, the user becomes eligible for
              a production API key (<code>sk_live_...</code>). Before that, only <code>sk_test_</code>
              sandbox keys are issued. Retry endpoint: <code>POST /v1/onboarding/kyc/retry</code>.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Pipeline Mermaid -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">At execution time</div>
          <h2>What actually runs inside the Pre-Execution Pipeline.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            The orchestrator calls the pipeline once. The pipeline runs the compliance checks in the
            order below. Any fail-closed reject is audited with a reason code and surfaced via webhook.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
sequenceDiagram
    participant O as Orchestrator
    participant P as PreExecutionPipeline
    participant KYC as KYC (Didit)
    participant KYA as KYA (agent)
    participant S as Sanctions (OFAC / Chainalysis)
    participant F as FIDES (trust graph)
    participant TR as Travel Rule (Notabene)
    participant SAR as SAR drafter
    participant L as Ledger

    O->>P: execute(intent)
    P->>KYC: user.kyc_status == verified?
    KYC-->>P: ok / denied
    P->>KYA: agent registered + active?
    KYA-->>P: ok / stale / suspended
    P->>S: screen(payee, payer, amount)
    S-->>P: clear / match / soft-match
    P->>F: trust_score(agent_did) ≥ threshold?
    F-->>P: tier + signals
    alt amount > $3K
      P->>TR: originator/beneficiary ready?
      TR-->>P: drafted / blocked
    end
    alt any anomaly signal
      P->>SAR: draft report
      SAR-->>P: queued for human filing
    end
    P->>L: log decision (approved | denied)
    P-->>O: verdict
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Providers table -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Providers</div>
          <h2>Which provider covers which pillar.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Every provider sits behind an interface in
            <code>packages/sardis-compliance/src/sardis_compliance/providers/</code>. Swaps are
            cost-of-one-file changes (Persona → Didit cost one PR).
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Pillar</th><th>Primary</th><th>Pluggable alternates</th><th>Status</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>KYC (humans)</td><td>Didit</td><td>Persona, Coinbase Verifications, Privado ID</td><td>Live</td></tr>
            <tr><td>KYB (businesses)</td><td>Persona</td><td>Circle Compliance, MiCA-specific flow</td><td>Live</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sanctions (entities)</td><td>OpenSanctions</td><td>OFAC (direct), Watchman, Marble</td><td>Live</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sanctions (on-chain)</td><td>Chainalysis</td><td>Scorechain, Elliptic (planned)</td><td>Live (Chainalysis); Elliptic planned</td></tr>
            <tr><td>PEP / adverse media</td><td>OpenSanctions</td><td>Marble</td><td>Live</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Travel Rule</td><td>Notabene</td><td>—</td><td>Schema + drafts live; VASP routing staged</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Identity / DID</td><td>FIDES</td><td>Privado ID</td><td>Live (migration 055)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SAR authoring</td><td>Sardis native</td><td>—</td><td>Drafts auto-generated; filing is human.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- FIDES + KYA detail -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Agent-native additions</div>
          <h2>FIDES + KYA — what human compliance frameworks can't cover.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            KYC/AML/Travel Rule were designed for humans and companies. Autonomous agents break both
            axes — they don't have passports and they aren't LLCs. Sardis fills the gap with two
            modules.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">FIDES — decentralized trust graph</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Migration 055 adds <code>did_mappings</code>, <code>trust_score_snapshots</code>, and
              <code>agents.fides_did</code> / <code>agents.agit_repo_hash</code> columns. An agent's
              DID is verified via signature; its trust score is recomputed from on-chain behavior,
              incident history, and cross-platform attestations. Router:
              <code>routers/fides_identity.py</code>. This is Efe's other open-standards project,
              embedded as a first-class compliance signal.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">KYA — agent lifecycle</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Eleven endpoints under <code>/v1/kya/*</code>: register, get, check, upgrade, suspend,
              reactivate, heartbeat, stale-sweep. Module: <code>sardis_compliance/kya.py</code>.
              <code>agit_policy_engine.py</code> consumes KYA state at decision time — a suspended or
              heartbeat-stale agent fails closed before the transaction reaches the wallet.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Data governance + enterprise -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Data governance + enterprise controls</div>
          <h2>Retention, export, SSO, and per-role RBAC.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Compliance doesn't end when the check passes. Regulators want retention schedules, GDPR
            wants export + deletion, and enterprise buyers want SSO before they write a PO.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Concern</th><th>Where it lives</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>PII classification</td>
              <td>Migration 042 · <code>data_classification</code></td>
              <td>Per-column PII type + retention days + anonymize-on-expiry. Seeds: users.email (730d, anonymize), wallets.address (1095d), access_audit_log.ip (90d, anonymize), payer_wallet_address (365d, anonymize).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Retention jobs</td>
              <td>Migration 042 · <code>data_retention_log</code></td>
              <td>Every purge run records rows purged, rows anonymized, duration. Operators can prove retention, not just promise it.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>GDPR export / deletion</td>
              <td>Router <code>data_export.py</code> · <code>compliance_export.py</code></td>
              <td>Per-subject export + delete endpoints. Export bundles are Merkle-anchored so users get tamper-evident copies.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>SAR 5-year retention</td>
              <td>Migration 011 · <code>suspicious_activity_reports</code></td>
              <td>FinCEN hard requirement. Schema designed for long-horizon archival, not just working-set queries.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>SSO (SAML / OIDC)</td>
              <td>Migration 043 · <code>sso_config</code></td>
              <td>Per-tenant SSO configuration — required for regulated enterprise buyers.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Advanced RBAC</td>
              <td>Migration 044 · <code>advanced_rbac</code></td>
              <td>Role/permission matrix beyond owner/admin/viewer — needed for segregation of duties in banking-adjacent orgs.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Identity registry</td>
              <td>Migration 011 · <code>identity_records</code></td>
              <td>TAP/AP2 attestation keys with versioning + revocation — the audit trail that says "this agent claimed this key at this time."</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Certification program -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Certification program</div>
          <h2>SOC 2 + PCI + ISO + GDPR + AIUC-1.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            External certifications that regulated buyers ask for, scoped to a one-year evidence
            collection program with a dedicated Trust Control Dashboard running alongside Sardis.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Framework</th><th>Scope</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>SOC 2 Type II</td><td>Security, availability, confidentiality</td><td>Every US enterprise procurement team asks for this. Without it, no deal.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>PCI DSS</td><td>Virtual cards flow (Stripe Issuing + planned direct)</td><td>Cardholder data environment; required once Sardis Cards GA.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>ISO 27001</td><td>ISMS — information security management</td><td>European + enterprise baseline; pairs with GDPR for EU buyers.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GDPR</td><td>EU personal data</td><td>Aligns with migration 042 retention + anonymize-on-expiry columns.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>AIUC-1</td><td>AI agent safety / governance</td><td>The new piece. KYA + FIDES + policy decisions map to AIUC-1 controls directly.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Endpoint surface -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Endpoint surface</div>
          <h2>What compliance exposes over HTTP.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Endpoint</th><th>Module</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/onboarding/kyc/initiate</code></td><td>kyc_onboarding.py</td><td>Start Didit session for dashboard user.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/onboarding/kyc/webhook</code></td><td>kyc_onboarding.py</td><td>Didit decision callback (x-api-key auth).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/onboarding/kyc/retry</code></td><td>kyc_onboarding.py</td><td>Reattempt after denial or document issue.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/kyc/verify</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Generic KYC inquiry (provider-agnostic).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /v1/compliance/kyc/&#123;agent_id&#125;</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Current KYC status.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/kya/register</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Register agent identity + attestation.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/kya/&#123;id&#125;/check</code> · <code>/upgrade</code> · <code>/suspend</code> · <code>/reactivate</code> · <code>/heartbeat</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Agent lifecycle state transitions.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/kya/stale/sweep</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Bulk expire stale-heartbeat agents.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/sanctions/screen</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Screen an entity / address.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/sanctions/screen-transaction</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Screen a full transaction (payer + payee + amount).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /v1/compliance/sanctions/check/&#123;address&#125;</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Cached lookup for a single address.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/sanctions/block</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Manual block push (incident response).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /v1/compliance/audit/recent</code> · <code>/audit/mandate/&#123;id&#125;</code> · <code>/audit/verify-chain</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Queryable compliance audit trail.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /v1/compliance/audit/evidence/export</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Signed evidence bundle for auditors.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/compliance/audit/evidence/verify-signature</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Verify a previously exported bundle.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /v1/compliance/webhooks/persona/verify</code></td><td>compliance.py</td><td>Persona fallback webhook verification.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /v1/fides/...</code></td><td>fides_identity.py</td><td>DID resolution + trust score queries.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Source of truth -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Source of truth</div>
          <h2>Where each control actually lives.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File / migration</th><th>What it owns</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-compliance/src/sardis_compliance/</code></td><td>The package. Modules: kyc · kyb · kya · sanctions · pep · adverse_media · travel_rule · sar · risk_scoring · audit_rotation · batch · reports · checks · marble · mica · circle_compliance · coinbase_verifications.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>…/providers/</code></td><td>didit · chainalysis · notabene · ofac · opensanctions · privado_id · scorechain · watchman. Behind one interface.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/server-api/src/sardis_server/routes/compliance/compliance.py</code></td><td>All <code>/v1/compliance/*</code> endpoints (KYC, KYA, sanctions, audit, evidence).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>…/routers/kyc_onboarding.py</code></td><td>Dashboard-facing KYC onboarding (Didit flow).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>…/routers/fides_identity.py</code></td><td>FIDES DID + trust score queries.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>…/routers/compliance_export.py</code></td><td>GDPR / regulator export bundles.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>migrations/010_kyb_verifications.sql</code></td><td>KYB tracking per organization.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>migrations/011_sar_and_identity_persistence.sql</code></td><td>SAR (FinCEN 5-yr) + identity_records.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>migrations/012_travel_rule.sql</code></td><td>FATF R.16 transfer records.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>migrations/042_data_governance.sql</code></td><td>PII classification + retention + anonymize-on-expiry.</td></tr>
